Product name: Rare Vintage 1940s French Powder Compact Complete With Lipstick,  Engraved & Engine Turned Base, Art Deco Compact
Description:
A beautiful large, solid brass compact, dating from 1940s. This compacts is in good, usable condition; it has some minor sign of wear, commensurate with its 70-plus years of age, but the mirror is clear and the hinges and clasps all work well. 
The lid is beautifully engraved with little fish with long fan-like tails swimming amongst sea plants. It is polished to a nice, subtle shine.
The base is engine turned and has only very minor signs of wear.
The compact opens by pressing a button on the side, revealing a self opening interior flap leading to the powder well. These 'nail saving' self opening lids were patented by Stratton in the 1940s and quickly adopted (and adapted) by other compact manufacturers. As soon as one opens the outer lid, the inner lid automatically pops open - no need to push buttons or slide levers and all those other nail breaking hazards! 
Inside the lipstick compartment here is a beautifully shaped lipstick holder with a bright red lipstick. Even the lipstick on its own, with its gracefully domed lid, is a lovely collectible item. 
Engraved 'Made in France' under the mirror.

Product name: Sam, the Peanut Man,  Lancaster, Pa.
Description:
This is a high quality sepia toned photograph taken by Greg Petrick  in the 70s in Lancaster Pa. Other sizes available. 
 "Sam, the Peanut Man," was actually Savas Vulopas. He came to Lancaster from Greece in 1918. He was one of downtown Lancaster's "characters."  He and his brother, Stergos Voulopos (who went by "Steve" and spelled his surname differently), operated various food shops in downtown Lancaster until the early '30s.  In 1932, Stergos opened and began operating the Manhattan Peanut Stand at 50 W. King St.  Meanwhile, Sam moved to Ephrata, where he operated Superior Dry Cleaners for nearly four decades. He also sold peanuts in Ephrata.  After Stergos died in 1971, Sam moved back to Lancaster. He ran the shop on West King until the end of 1980. He roasted his last peanuts just after Christmas. He said he had been selling about 10 tons of peanuts a year.   He was 98 years old when he died in 1999.
